1
00:01:05,820 --> 00:01:08,471
Shh. Hey.

2
00:01:12,100 --> 00:01:14,387
<i>Bathsheba Everdene.</i>

3
00:01:15,100 --> 00:01:16,431
<i>Bathsheba.</i>

4
00:01:18,220 --> 00:01:19,984
<i>The name has always
sounded strange to me.</i>

5
00:01:20,060 --> 00:01:21,585
<i>I don't like to hear it
said out loud.</i>

6
00:01:24,420 --> 00:01:26,991
<i>My parents died
when I was very young,</i>

7
00:01:27,060 --> 00:01:29,791
<i>so there's no one to ask
where it came from.</i>

8
00:01:30,700 --> 00:01:33,624
<i>I've grown accustomed
to being on my own.</i>

9
00:01:33,940 --> 00:01:36,750
<i>Some say even too accustomed.</i>

10
00:01:37,740 --> 00:01:40,425
<i>Too independent.</i>

11
00:03:13,020 --> 00:03:14,351
Miss!

12
00:03:17,860 --> 00:03:19,146
Miss!

13
00:03:34,820 --> 00:03:36,390
My scarf.

14
00:03:36,940 --> 00:03:38,351
I lost it.

15
00:03:39,460 --> 00:03:41,064
You must be Farmer Oak.

16
00:03:41,140 --> 00:03:42,790
Gabriel, yes.

17
00:03:43,220 --> 00:03:44,904
My aunt's told me about you.

18
00:03:44,980 --> 00:03:46,789
I'm working on her farm
for the winter.

19
00:03:50,380 --> 00:03:51,984
This is your land.

20
00:03:53,540 --> 00:03:55,622
I'm trespassing.

21
00:03:55,700 --> 00:03:57,543
You're welcome here.

22
00:04:10,660 --> 00:04:12,025
Good afternoon, Farmer Oak.

23
00:04:12,300 --> 00:04:14,189
Good afternoon, miss.

24
00:04:44,220 --> 00:04:45,710
Come by, George.

25
00:04:46,100 --> 00:04:49,627
George, away!
Enough, George!

26
00:04:49,740 --> 00:04:51,185
Enough!

27
00:04:52,260 --> 00:04:54,262
Stand. Stand.

28
00:04:54,700 --> 00:04:56,065
George, stand.

29
00:04:57,860 --> 00:04:59,021
Away!

30
00:04:59,460 --> 00:05:00,621
Away!

31
00:05:01,780 --> 00:05:04,067
George, away!

32
00:05:05,860 --> 00:05:07,783
He doesn't know when to stop,
Young George.

33
00:05:08,300 --> 00:05:09,665
What's this one called?

34
00:05:09,740 --> 00:05:10,980
Old George.

35
00:05:13,740 --> 00:05:15,230
Old George.

36
00:05:15,620 --> 00:05:17,224
So you find me amusing, do you?

37
00:06:07,100 --> 00:06:09,182
Goodness,
it's Mr. Oak.

38
00:06:19,980 --> 00:06:22,300
...and after that
she was gonna be a governess.

39
00:06:22,380 --> 00:06:23,791
But she was far too wild.

40
00:06:23,940 --> 00:06:25,704
Always has been.

41
00:06:25,780 --> 00:06:26,781
Oh!

42
00:06:34,060 --> 00:06:37,382
Miss Bathsheba Everdene.

43
00:06:38,340 --> 00:06:40,468
I've brought you a lamb.

44
00:06:40,980 --> 00:06:42,869
Oh!

45
00:06:43,620 --> 00:06:48,308
Thank you, Mr. Oak.
He's such a dear thing.

46
00:06:48,460 --> 00:06:50,701
He's come too soon
and won't last the winter,

47
00:06:50,820 --> 00:06:52,982
so I thought you'd
like to rear it instead.

48
00:06:53,340 --> 00:06:55,581
Thank you, that's very kind.

49
00:06:56,380 --> 00:06:58,587
I'll make some tea.

50
00:07:01,660 --> 00:07:03,310
The lamb is not why I came.

51
00:07:03,500 --> 00:07:05,150
Go on.

52
00:07:08,020 --> 00:07:10,671
Well, Miss Everdene,
I wanted to ask...

53
00:07:11,260 --> 00:07:12,989
Would you like to marry me?

54
00:07:16,260 --> 00:07:17,830
I've never asked anyone before.

55
00:07:20,060 --> 00:07:21,061
No.

56
00:07:22,220 --> 00:07:24,029
I should hope not.

57
00:07:25,340 --> 00:07:26,501
Well...

58
00:07:27,540 --> 00:07:30,111
Perhaps I, erm, I should...

59
00:07:32,100 --> 00:07:33,340
Perhaps I should leave.
Mr. Oak,

60
00:07:33,420 --> 00:07:35,184
there are things to consider.

61
00:07:36,620 --> 00:07:38,349
Is someone waiting for you?

62
00:07:38,700 --> 00:07:41,863
No, but that doesn't
mean I'll marry you.

63
00:07:43,060 --> 00:07:44,425
Good day to you, then.

64
00:07:53,420 --> 00:07:55,024
Mr. Oak!

65
00:07:55,740 --> 00:07:58,903
Mr. Oak! Wait!

66
00:08:01,700 --> 00:08:04,465
I didn't say I wouldn't
marry you, either.

67
00:08:06,700 --> 00:08:08,429
I haven't ever really
thought about it.

68
00:08:09,060 --> 00:08:12,223
I have 100 acres and 200 sheep.

69
00:08:13,980 --> 00:08:16,904
If I pay off the money,
the farm is ours.

70
00:08:18,380 --> 00:08:20,667
You could have a piano
in a year or two.

71
00:08:20,780 --> 00:08:24,068
Flowers and birds
and a frame for cucumbers.

72
00:08:24,420 --> 00:08:25,945
A baby or two.

73
00:08:26,060 --> 00:08:27,221
Mr. Oak...
Or more.

74
00:08:28,580 --> 00:08:30,423
I will always be there for you.

75
00:08:32,100 --> 00:08:34,262
Mr. Oak, I don't
want a husband.

76
00:08:34,940 --> 00:08:37,466
I'd hate to be
some man's property.

77
00:08:38,780 --> 00:08:40,384
I shouldn't mind being
a bride at a wedding

78
00:08:40,460 --> 00:08:42,428
if I could be one
without getting a husband.

79
00:08:42,820 --> 00:08:44,663
That's stupid talk.

80
00:08:46,340 --> 00:08:48,581
You are better off
than I, Mr. Oak.

81
00:08:49,100 --> 00:08:51,341
I have an education
and nothing more.

82
00:08:51,460 --> 00:08:53,110
You could do much,
much better than me.

83
00:08:53,180 --> 00:08:54,625
That's not the reason.

84
00:08:59,700 --> 00:09:00,820
I'm too independent for you.

85
00:09:02,700 --> 00:09:03,861
If I ever were to marry,

86
00:09:03,940 --> 00:09:05,146
I'd want somebody to tame me

87
00:09:05,260 --> 00:09:06,944
and you'd never
be able to do it.

88
00:09:08,780 --> 00:09:10,862
You'd grow to despise me.

89
00:09:13,340 --> 00:09:14,785
I would not.

90
00:09:16,980 --> 00:09:18,345
Ever.

91
00:09:22,940 --> 00:09:25,227
Good-bye, Miss Everdene.

92
00:10:25,180 --> 00:10:26,750
What is it, old boy?

93
00:10:29,700 --> 00:10:31,225
Stay here.

94
00:10:35,180 --> 00:10:36,750
Stay here, Old George.

95
00:10:36,860 --> 00:10:38,624
Stay here.

96
00:10:48,060 --> 00:10:49,550
George!

97
00:11:01,820 --> 00:11:03,902
George!

98
00:11:50,340 --> 00:11:51,944
No!

99
00:12:59,540 --> 00:13:00,746
It's all yours.

100
00:13:12,020 --> 00:13:14,182
We take no pleasure in this.

101
00:13:16,220 --> 00:13:18,382
We wish
you well, Mr. Oak.

102
00:13:33,420 --> 00:13:34,581
Bathsheba.

103
00:13:39,420 --> 00:13:40,945
What is it?

104
00:13:41,540 --> 00:13:45,261
My love. It's your
poor uncle's will.

105
00:13:46,220 --> 00:13:47,790
What does it say?

106
00:13:49,220 --> 00:13:50,631
Read it.

107
00:13:51,820 --> 00:13:53,231
Read!

108
00:13:55,140 --> 00:13:59,065
He's left you everything.
It's all yours.

109
00:13:59,940 --> 00:14:01,146
Oh!

110
00:14:01,940 --> 00:14:03,908
Oh, my goodness.

111
00:14:05,500 --> 00:14:07,662
Take care, you hear.

112
00:14:15,780 --> 00:14:17,191
Walk on.

113
00:14:22,860 --> 00:14:24,191
Bye.

114
00:14:44,500 --> 00:14:46,707
So who will join us, lads?

115
00:14:47,500 --> 00:14:48,945
Which one of you fine boys

116
00:14:49,020 --> 00:14:50,670
will put on the scarlet uniform

117
00:14:50,780 --> 00:14:54,148
and proudly serve
his Queen and country?

118
00:14:55,140 --> 00:14:56,630
See the world.

119
00:14:57,780 --> 00:15:00,624
Form an orderly line,
gentlemen, at the front.

120
00:15:00,980 --> 00:15:01,981
This gentleman in the straw hat,

121
00:15:02,060 --> 00:15:03,107
step forward, sir.

122
00:15:03,180 --> 00:15:04,830
That's my sweetheart,
right there.

123
00:15:05,300 --> 00:15:08,622
You, sir,
next to the pretty lady.

124
00:15:09,220 --> 00:15:11,188
There's a good strong
figure of a man.

125
00:15:11,540 --> 00:15:12,905
Join us, sir.

126
00:15:13,300 --> 00:15:15,223
Go on. You'd make
a fine soldier.

127
00:15:15,300 --> 00:15:17,189
Always room in the ranks for
a gentleman of your caliber.

128
00:15:17,300 --> 00:15:18,904
It's a roof
over your head. Food.

129
00:15:21,500 --> 00:15:23,707
Who wants a fine wage?

130
00:15:23,820 --> 00:15:25,151
Excuse me.

131
00:15:25,220 --> 00:15:27,905
You might try Weatherbury.
If you're looking for work,

132
00:15:27,980 --> 00:15:30,108
there's a farm there
needs all the help it can get.

133
00:15:30,220 --> 00:15:31,824
Yes.
The young lad there.

134
00:15:31,900 --> 00:15:33,902
I will. Thank you.

135
00:15:33,980 --> 00:15:35,266
And your
friend as well.

136
00:15:35,340 --> 00:15:37,183
You should have a cloak
for a day like this.

137
00:15:39,020 --> 00:15:40,545
Francis
will take care of me.

138
00:15:43,100 --> 00:15:44,750
We are to be married soon.

139
00:15:45,700 --> 00:15:47,111
Good-bye.

140
00:15:47,220 --> 00:15:48,824
Come on,
a decent wage.

141
00:15:48,900 --> 00:15:50,425
Make your family proud.

142
00:15:50,540 --> 00:15:53,749
Food, shelter.
Who will join us?

143
00:16:46,620 --> 00:16:48,907
Go and wake up
the other farms!

144
00:16:48,980 --> 00:16:51,187
Get them down here!
We need more hands!

145
00:16:51,300 --> 00:16:52,461
We need
more men now!

146
00:16:52,580 --> 00:16:53,581
Wake them up!

147
00:16:54,340 --> 00:16:56,820
Go and get
the Smith brothers first.

148
00:16:56,940 --> 00:16:59,466
Protect yourself,
the fire's spreading!

149
00:17:00,740 --> 00:17:02,151
Who's in charge here?

150
00:17:02,260 --> 00:17:05,503
We're losing the ricks!
The rick is lost.

151
00:17:06,100 --> 00:17:07,864
We need to save the barn.
Come on, help me!

152
00:17:08,620 --> 00:17:11,908
Come on, get some more water!
Get some more water!

153
00:17:13,100 --> 00:17:15,580
We need to push
this out. Come on!

154
00:17:15,700 --> 00:17:16,986
Heave!

155
00:17:19,100 --> 00:17:20,784
Heave!

156
00:17:21,100 --> 00:17:22,431
Heave!

157
00:17:23,820 --> 00:17:26,221
Come on, push!

158
00:17:48,980 --> 00:17:51,631
Everybody out!
Everybody out!

159
00:17:56,020 --> 00:17:58,261
Water!
More over here!

160
00:17:58,340 --> 00:17:59,387
The barn's going up!

161
00:17:59,460 --> 00:18:01,827
Get the sacks out,
the root's about to go!

162
00:18:18,180 --> 00:18:19,989
What's he doing up there?

163
00:18:20,060 --> 00:18:22,666
We lose the barn,
we lose everything.

164
00:19:02,940 --> 00:19:05,511
Joseph,
bring those brooms over

165
00:19:05,580 --> 00:19:07,230
and let's get this sorted out.

166
00:19:08,220 --> 00:19:11,064
Look sharp, men,
the farmer's here.

167
00:19:25,220 --> 00:19:27,222
Mr. Oak, is that you?

168
00:19:32,100 --> 00:19:33,590
Perhaps you want
a shepherd, ma'am?

169
00:19:37,620 --> 00:19:40,271
I owe you an immense
debt, Mr. Oak.

170
00:19:40,820 --> 00:19:43,141
If I'd have lost all of this,
I'd have lost my farm.

171
00:19:43,260 --> 00:19:44,307
Your farm?

172
00:19:44,740 --> 00:19:45,980
My inheritance.

173
00:19:46,100 --> 00:19:49,024
My home, too, for a while
when my parents died.

174
00:19:50,340 --> 00:19:53,184
When my uncle passed away,
he left it to me.

175
00:19:54,260 --> 00:19:56,945
Of course,
it's a little ragged now,

176
00:19:57,740 --> 00:20:00,584
but this once used to be
the finest farm for miles.

177
00:20:00,780 --> 00:20:03,260
And I intend
to make it so again.

178
00:20:04,780 --> 00:20:06,300
Perhaps you find
the idea preposterous.

179
00:20:06,980 --> 00:20:09,426
I no longer have that luxury.

180
00:20:11,100 --> 00:20:13,865
I'm truly sorry to hear
of your loss, Mr. Oak,

181
00:20:13,940 --> 00:20:15,430
but if our reversal of fortune

182
00:20:15,500 --> 00:20:16,911
causes you any embarrassment...

183
00:20:16,980 --> 00:20:19,381
Not at all, ma'am.

184
00:20:24,100 --> 00:20:26,546
Billy Smallbury?
9 and 8 pence.

185
00:20:28,620 --> 00:20:30,384
Joseph Poorgrass?

186
00:20:30,860 --> 00:20:32,021
Go on, Joseph.

187
00:20:32,180 --> 00:20:33,341
Go on, lad.

188
00:20:33,460 --> 00:20:35,064
Hat off.

189
00:20:36,300 --> 00:20:37,870
And what do you do, Joseph?

190
00:20:38,020 --> 00:20:39,590
I does general things.

191
00:20:39,660 --> 00:20:40,946
And in spring I shoot the rooks

192
00:20:41,020 --> 00:20:42,180
and help at pig killing, sir.

193
00:20:43,300 --> 00:20:44,347
I mean ma'am.

194
00:20:45,900 --> 00:20:49,746
7 and 9 pence.
And another 9 because I'm new.

195
00:20:49,820 --> 00:20:51,663
Thank you, ma'am.

196
00:20:55,860 --> 00:20:57,862
Now, Fanny Robbin?

197
00:21:00,140 --> 00:21:02,268
Where is Fanny Robbin?

198
00:21:03,020 --> 00:21:04,021
Where is she?

199
00:21:05,220 --> 00:21:07,382
She's run away, ma'am.

200
00:21:07,980 --> 00:21:09,789
She's gone off
with a soldier, ma'am.

201
00:21:09,860 --> 00:21:12,067
Not a soldier, a sergeant.

202
00:21:16,340 --> 00:21:17,830
Bailiff Pennyways?

203
00:21:22,860 --> 00:21:25,431
Here is 10 shillings
and a further 10.

204
00:21:25,860 --> 00:21:27,385
Why?

205
00:21:28,340 --> 00:21:30,946
This ends our association.
You are dismissed.

206
00:21:31,340 --> 00:21:32,910
I beg pardon, miss?

207
00:21:33,020 --> 00:21:34,021
When my uncle was alive,

208
00:21:34,100 --> 00:21:36,228
this was a fine,
productive farm.

209
00:21:36,700 --> 00:21:39,021
Since his death,
it has fallen into ruin.

210
00:21:40,540 --> 00:21:42,030
I can only assume...
Now see here, miss.

211
00:21:42,100 --> 00:21:43,261
You can't get rid
of people like that.

212
00:21:43,380 --> 00:21:44,381
I have resolved
to have no bailiff at all,

213
00:21:44,460 --> 00:21:45,507
I have decided
to manage everything.

214
00:21:45,580 --> 00:21:47,582
Mr. Pennyways, if you'll
listen to me for a moment.

215
00:21:47,700 --> 00:21:50,624
Mr. Pennyways, a fire
threatened to destroy the barn

216
00:21:50,700 --> 00:21:52,862
and you are nowhere to be found.

217
00:21:57,740 --> 00:22:00,789
I have no use for a man
like you, Mr. Pennyways.

218
00:22:01,900 --> 00:22:02,947
You are dismissed.

219
00:22:12,420 --> 00:22:14,300
Get out
while you can, if I were you.

220
00:22:25,420 --> 00:22:27,263
Now you've all met
our new shepherd, Mr. Oak.

221
00:22:29,100 --> 00:22:31,262
You understand
your duties, Mr. Oak?

222
00:22:32,460 --> 00:22:34,462
If I don't, I'll ask, ma'am.

223
00:22:40,260 --> 00:22:43,423
From now on, you have
a mistress, not a master.

224
00:22:44,180 --> 00:22:45,700
I don't yet know
my talents in farming,

225
00:22:45,780 --> 00:22:47,270
but I shall do my best.

226
00:22:48,260 --> 00:22:49,620
Don't suppose,
because I'm a woman,

227
00:22:49,700 --> 00:22:50,781
I don't know
the difference between

228
00:22:50,860 --> 00:22:52,464
bad goings-on and good.

229
00:22:52,620 --> 00:22:54,782
I shall be up
before you're awake.

230
00:22:55,340 --> 00:22:57,104
I shall be a-field
before you are up.

231
00:22:58,020 --> 00:23:00,785
It is my intention
to astonish you all.

232
00:23:03,780 --> 00:23:05,305
Back to work, please.

233
00:23:24,620 --> 00:23:26,509
Perhaps I should wait here?

234
00:23:26,620 --> 00:23:27,906
No.

235
00:23:28,460 --> 00:23:31,987
Nonsense, Liddy.
You're my companion.

236
00:23:32,060 --> 00:23:33,061
All of these?

237
00:23:33,220 --> 00:23:34,221
All of them.

238
00:23:36,540 --> 00:23:37,541
Head high, Liddy.

239
00:23:37,660 --> 00:23:39,503
If they stare, do not hesitate.

240
00:23:46,820 --> 00:23:49,426
Remember, we have as much
right to be here as anyone.

241
00:23:53,740 --> 00:23:54,980
Good morning.

242
00:24:11,860 --> 00:24:13,385
Liddy, if you lay things out.

243
00:24:13,540 --> 00:24:15,110
Yes, miss.

244
00:24:16,180 --> 00:24:19,787
Gentlemen, shall we
get back to business?

245
00:24:29,380 --> 00:24:30,745
There you go, sir.

246
00:24:30,860 --> 00:24:32,460
If you feel it,
you can feel the quality.

247
00:24:33,020 --> 00:24:34,021
This is fine grain, miss.

248
00:24:34,100 --> 00:24:35,181
Thank you.

249
00:24:37,860 --> 00:24:40,067
Perhaps we should leave, miss.

250
00:24:43,420 --> 00:24:45,149
But none of it
as good as this lot.

251
00:24:45,220 --> 00:24:46,381
It's good stuff,
I'll grant you that.

252
00:24:46,540 --> 00:24:47,780
Well, it's up to you.
If you wanna go elsewhere...

253
00:24:47,900 --> 00:24:48,981
No, no, no...

254
00:24:49,060 --> 00:24:50,266
Farmer Stone?

255
00:24:50,900 --> 00:24:54,382
It's Miss Everdene.
Farmer Everdene's niece.

256
00:24:55,900 --> 00:24:58,221
He talked about you
with such great admiration.

257
00:25:01,060 --> 00:25:02,744
Of course, you're welcome
to try elsewhere,

258
00:25:02,820 --> 00:25:05,983
but I think you'll find the
grain as good as it's ever been.

259
00:25:10,580 --> 00:25:11,945
Mr. Stone?
How much?

260
00:25:12,060 --> 00:25:13,903
£5 a quarter.

261
00:25:14,060 --> 00:25:15,949
£3-10 shillings.

262
00:25:16,260 --> 00:25:17,460
It's the same grain,
Mr. Stone.

263
00:25:17,500 --> 00:25:19,787
You paid my uncle £5.

264
00:25:19,900 --> 00:25:21,743
£3-10.

265
00:25:23,620 --> 00:25:26,021
This gentleman
will pay me the proper price.

266
00:25:28,580 --> 00:25:30,423
Apparently not, no.

267
00:25:30,940 --> 00:25:31,987
£4.

268
00:25:32,100 --> 00:25:33,101
£4-10.

269
00:25:33,260 --> 00:25:34,671
£4-05.

270
00:25:36,020 --> 00:25:37,351
Perhaps I should move on.

271
00:25:38,180 --> 00:25:40,342
Liddy, would you help me
with this gentleman?

272
00:25:40,420 --> 00:25:41,865
Of course.

273
00:25:42,620 --> 00:25:44,622
Perhaps you'd like a sample?

274
00:25:45,100 --> 00:25:46,989
How much?
£5 a quarter.

275
00:25:47,780 --> 00:25:49,464
Very well.

276
00:25:51,460 --> 00:25:53,144
£4-10.

277
00:26:04,220 --> 00:26:07,622
<i>Jerusalem the golden</i>

278
00:26:07,780 --> 00:26:12,866
<i>With milk and honey blest</i>

279
00:26:13,460 --> 00:26:18,990
<i>Beneath thy contemplation</i>

280
00:26:19,300 --> 00:26:24,306
<i>Sink heart and voice oppressed</i>

281
00:26:25,220 --> 00:26:30,386
He's rich, he's handsome.
He sends the local girls mad.

282
00:26:30,820 --> 00:26:34,302
The Taylor sisters
worked on him for two years.

283
00:26:34,380 --> 00:26:36,542
Jane Perkins spent £20
on new clothes

284
00:26:36,660 --> 00:26:37,741
and might as well have

285
00:26:37,820 --> 00:26:39,868
thrown the money out the window.

286
00:26:42,100 --> 00:26:45,900
It's said, when he was young,
his sweetheart jilted him.

287
00:26:47,660 --> 00:26:49,662
People always say that.

288
00:26:50,180 --> 00:26:53,343
Women don't jilt men.
Men jilt us.

289
00:26:53,860 --> 00:26:56,181
Did someone jilt you, miss?

290
00:26:56,500 --> 00:26:58,389
Certainly not.

291
00:27:01,860 --> 00:27:04,022
A man did ask to marry me once.

292
00:27:04,100 --> 00:27:05,340
Some time ago.

293
00:27:05,780 --> 00:27:08,226
But I was too restless
to be tied down.

294
00:27:08,340 --> 00:27:11,708
What a luxury, to have a choice.

295
00:27:13,020 --> 00:27:16,911
"Kiss my foot, sir, my face
is for mouths of consequence."

296
00:27:17,020 --> 00:27:18,943
It wasn't like that at all.

297
00:27:19,860 --> 00:27:21,225
Why?

298
00:27:22,300 --> 00:27:23,745
Did you love him?

299
00:27:24,300 --> 00:27:26,701
No, but I rather liked him.

300
00:27:27,780 --> 00:27:30,067
Anyway, it's impossible now.

301
00:27:43,780 --> 00:27:45,066
Mr. Boldwood.

302
00:27:45,580 --> 00:27:46,741
Don't shoot me, please.

303
00:27:47,460 --> 00:27:49,747
I had no intention
of shooting you.

304
00:27:52,060 --> 00:27:54,586
It's Miss Everdene.
Your neighbor.

305
00:27:55,900 --> 00:27:58,107
Farmer Everdene's niece.

306
00:28:01,340 --> 00:28:02,387
I'm managing the farm alone now.

307
00:28:02,460 --> 00:28:03,461
Perhaps you've heard?

308
00:28:03,620 --> 00:28:05,941
Yes, I'm sure
you'll do very well.

309
00:28:07,660 --> 00:28:08,821
In the circumstances.

310
00:28:12,660 --> 00:28:16,062
Well, as you say,
we're neighbors.

311
00:28:28,860 --> 00:28:30,703
Look what
I've got here.

312
00:28:31,940 --> 00:28:32,941
What is it?

313
00:28:33,100 --> 00:28:34,101
Listen to this.

314
00:28:34,180 --> 00:28:35,944
"The rose is red The violet blue

315
00:28:36,100 --> 00:28:39,104
"Carnation's sweet
And so are you"

316
00:28:40,940 --> 00:28:42,669
It's a Valentine's card.

317
00:28:42,780 --> 00:28:44,942
I'm going to send it
to Joseph Poorgrass

318
00:28:45,020 --> 00:28:47,705
just to see the look
of panic on his stupid face.

319
00:28:47,820 --> 00:28:50,664
Poor boy. It's a little bit
far-fetched, isn't it?

320
00:28:51,340 --> 00:28:53,991
What about
Mr. Oak, then?

321
00:28:54,060 --> 00:28:56,666
No. Not Mr. Oak.

322
00:28:58,140 --> 00:28:59,824
Imagine if we sent it
to Mr. Boldwood.

323
00:29:01,700 --> 00:29:04,306
Ignoring you like that,
all high and mighty.

324
00:29:04,980 --> 00:29:06,550
Mr. Boldwood?

325
00:29:08,300 --> 00:29:09,904
Perhaps not?

326
00:29:10,300 --> 00:29:11,665
Why not?

327
00:29:11,820 --> 00:29:14,300
Because I don't think
he'll see the humor.

328
00:29:14,980 --> 00:29:15,981
Perhaps he wouldn't,

329
00:29:16,060 --> 00:29:17,300
perhaps it's too much.

330
00:29:17,420 --> 00:29:19,548
Mr. Boldwood.

331
00:29:19,700 --> 00:29:21,828
You're right.
Perhaps it is.

332
00:29:22,980 --> 00:29:24,744
So we're gonna toss for it.

333
00:29:24,820 --> 00:29:25,821
Liddy!

334
00:29:25,900 --> 00:29:27,265
Come on.

335
00:29:29,740 --> 00:29:31,504
Open, Joseph.

336
00:29:31,660 --> 00:29:33,389
No, Jan Coggan.

337
00:29:33,540 --> 00:29:37,511
Open, Jan Coggan.
Closed, Boldwood.

338
00:30:47,140 --> 00:30:48,744
Sergeant Troy, 11:00.

339
00:30:48,900 --> 00:30:50,504
Yes, Sergeant Troy. And?

340
00:30:50,620 --> 00:30:52,782
Miss Fanny Robbin.

341
00:30:52,940 --> 00:30:55,147
Welcome. Step down the front.

342
00:31:28,060 --> 00:31:29,505
Where is she?

343
00:31:29,660 --> 00:31:31,071
I don't know.

344
00:31:33,340 --> 00:31:34,751
Here she comes.

345
00:31:40,100 --> 00:31:41,340
Oh.

346
00:31:50,780 --> 00:31:52,544
Sorry I'm late, old boy.

347
00:31:53,820 --> 00:31:55,151
Not long now.

348
00:32:16,540 --> 00:32:19,862
Dearly beloved, we are
gathered here in the sight...

349
00:32:24,740 --> 00:32:26,742
I can only wait
a few more minutes.

350
00:32:26,860 --> 00:32:28,225
She'll be here.

351
00:32:54,980 --> 00:32:56,823
What do you
think is happening?

352
00:32:57,660 --> 00:33:00,106
I don't think
she's coming, old boy.

353
00:33:30,060 --> 00:33:32,745
Come on. Go on, off you go.
That's it. Go on.

354
00:33:33,420 --> 00:33:34,660
Morning, my love.

355
00:33:34,820 --> 00:33:36,060
Come on.

356
00:33:39,260 --> 00:33:40,864
Bring them in, John.

357
00:33:46,260 --> 00:33:47,307
Grab this one.

358
00:33:47,380 --> 00:33:48,620
Miss Everdene's here now,

359
00:33:48,700 --> 00:33:49,781
so you better do your best work.

360
00:33:49,900 --> 00:33:51,345
I'm looking at you, Coggan.

361
00:33:51,420 --> 00:33:52,910
Yeah,
you keep quiet, Liddy.

362
00:34:01,940 --> 00:34:02,987
What you doing?

363
00:34:05,820 --> 00:34:07,709
Perhaps you'd care
to lend a hand?

364
00:34:08,660 --> 00:34:10,071
You don't think I would?

365
00:34:10,220 --> 00:34:11,631
No, you wouldn't.

366
00:34:12,980 --> 00:34:14,470
Come here.

367
00:34:18,780 --> 00:34:20,350
There,
she's getting in.

368
00:34:22,740 --> 00:34:24,310
Well done, ma'am.

369
00:34:46,740 --> 00:34:49,744
Gangway through.
Hey, Joseph. Joseph, look.

370
00:35:27,500 --> 00:35:29,707
Good morning,
Mr. Boldwood.

371
00:35:32,660 --> 00:35:33,900
Miss Everdene.

372
00:35:33,980 --> 00:35:37,985
Mr. Boldwood wondered if
he might have a word with you.

373
00:35:41,580 --> 00:35:44,789
Mr. Boldwood.
Of course.

374
00:35:45,900 --> 00:35:50,349
One thousand acres.
A mix of arable and livestock.

375
00:35:51,020 --> 00:35:52,385
Adjacent to Everdene.

376
00:35:52,780 --> 00:35:56,227
An orchard. Glasshouse.

377
00:35:57,460 --> 00:35:59,428
I have some interesting pigs.

378
00:36:02,020 --> 00:36:04,182
Some other time, perhaps.

379
00:36:09,260 --> 00:36:10,625
Thank you.

380
00:36:21,620 --> 00:36:24,305
You have a very beautiful house.

381
00:36:29,780 --> 00:36:31,111
Mr. Boldwood?

382
00:36:34,140 --> 00:36:35,505
Miss Everdene.

383
00:36:37,340 --> 00:36:38,865
I want

384
00:36:40,020 --> 00:36:43,024
very much, more than anything,

385
00:36:44,100 --> 00:36:45,909
to have you as my wife.

386
00:36:46,700 --> 00:36:49,704
Miss Everdene, marry me.

387
00:36:53,900 --> 00:36:54,901
I...

388
00:36:56,660 --> 00:36:58,662
I feel...

389
00:37:01,180 --> 00:37:04,389
Though I respect you very much,

390
00:37:06,740 --> 00:37:10,062
I do not feel
what would justify me

391
00:37:13,660 --> 00:37:15,981
in accepting your offer.

392
00:37:20,020 --> 00:37:23,502
I have known
disappointments before,

393
00:37:25,100 --> 00:37:26,943
but I would never have
asked in this instance

394
00:37:27,020 --> 00:37:28,829
had I not been, er,

395
00:37:29,940 --> 00:37:31,704
led to believe...

396
00:37:33,020 --> 00:37:36,661
Unless...
Unless I am mistaken.

397
00:37:38,380 --> 00:37:39,905
The valentine.

398
00:37:41,300 --> 00:37:42,381
No, you're not mistaken,

399
00:37:42,460 --> 00:37:44,588
but I should never have sent it.

400
00:37:45,900 --> 00:37:48,710
Forgive me, it was thoughtless
to disturb your peace of mind.

401
00:37:48,780 --> 00:37:50,305
So you meant it as a joke?

402
00:37:50,380 --> 00:37:53,589
No. No, not as a joke.

403
00:37:55,180 --> 00:37:59,071
Not exactly.
It was impetuous.

404
00:37:59,180 --> 00:38:00,306
I see.

405
00:38:01,500 --> 00:38:03,548
Perhaps you think I am too old?

406
00:38:03,820 --> 00:38:06,630
But I will care for you
more than anyone your own age.

407
00:38:07,140 --> 00:38:09,029
I'm sure you would...
I will protect you.

408
00:38:10,100 --> 00:38:12,546
You shall have dresses,

409
00:38:13,660 --> 00:38:16,823
a gig. Uh, a piano.

410
00:38:20,180 --> 00:38:21,511
I amuse you?

411
00:38:23,300 --> 00:38:24,665
No.

412
00:38:25,860 --> 00:38:27,350
It's only...

413
00:38:28,500 --> 00:38:30,502
I have a piano.

414
00:38:31,940 --> 00:38:34,420
And I have my own farm.

415
00:38:35,540 --> 00:38:37,190
And I have no need
for a husband,

416
00:38:38,180 --> 00:38:41,309
no matter how honored
I am by the offer.

417
00:38:46,740 --> 00:38:49,107
I think I'd like to return home.

418
00:38:49,260 --> 00:38:52,184
Yes, er... I'll, er...

419
00:38:52,900 --> 00:38:55,221
I'll get someone to drive you.

420
00:38:55,820 --> 00:38:58,346
Mr. Boldwood,
I've made you miserable.

421
00:38:58,460 --> 00:39:00,030
It was very wicked of me.

422
00:39:00,100 --> 00:39:02,102
Will you reconsider?

423
00:39:04,900 --> 00:39:06,743
Let me think.

424
00:39:09,300 --> 00:39:10,506
Yes.

425
00:39:11,660 --> 00:39:13,628
Yes, I'll give you time.

426
00:39:14,780 --> 00:39:16,464
I will wait.

427
00:39:41,980 --> 00:39:43,550
You're working
late, Mr. Oak.

428
00:39:48,700 --> 00:39:50,623
Will you teach me?

429
00:39:51,820 --> 00:39:53,151
Here.

430
00:39:54,620 --> 00:39:56,145
Spin the wheel.

431
00:39:56,900 --> 00:39:58,902
Incline it, like that.

432
00:40:00,260 --> 00:40:02,422
And slide it gently.
Spin the wheel.

433
00:40:05,060 --> 00:40:08,507
Bit faster. Like that.
Very good.

434
00:40:10,060 --> 00:40:11,346
Now slide it.

435
00:40:11,500 --> 00:40:12,865
I... It's...

436
00:40:13,900 --> 00:40:16,267
Getting stuck.

437
00:40:23,220 --> 00:40:24,949
I wanted to ask,

438
00:40:25,540 --> 00:40:27,781
did the men say anything
today about Mr. Boldwood?

439
00:40:27,860 --> 00:40:28,941
They did.

440
00:40:29,100 --> 00:40:30,147
What did they say?

441
00:40:30,460 --> 00:40:33,464
That you'd be married
before the end of the year.

442
00:40:33,780 --> 00:40:35,305
Come on.

443
00:40:37,540 --> 00:40:39,463
Well, I'd like you
to contradict it, to the men.

444
00:40:40,380 --> 00:40:41,870
Well, Bathsheba...

445
00:40:42,060 --> 00:40:43,585
"Miss Everdene," please.

446
00:40:46,380 --> 00:40:48,667
If Mr. Boldwood did really
speak of marriage,

447
00:40:48,820 --> 00:40:51,027
I'm not going to tell
stories just to please you.

448
00:40:52,620 --> 00:40:54,782
I just said I wanted you
to mention to the men

449
00:40:54,860 --> 00:40:57,101
that it might not be true
I was going to marry him.

450
00:40:57,180 --> 00:40:59,342
I could say that if you wish.

451
00:40:59,420 --> 00:41:01,388
But I could also give you an
opinion on what you've done.

452
00:41:01,500 --> 00:41:04,424
I dare say, but I don't want
your opinion, Mr. Oak.

453
00:41:06,940 --> 00:41:09,068
I suppose not.

454
00:41:20,420 --> 00:41:22,422
Well, what is your opinion?

455
00:41:23,420 --> 00:41:25,184
That you're greatly to blame
for playing pranks

456
00:41:25,260 --> 00:41:27,422
on a man like Mr. Boldwood.

457
00:41:28,980 --> 00:41:31,108
Your actions were
unworthy of you.

458
00:41:31,380 --> 00:41:36,705
Unworthy? May I ask
where my unworthiness lies?

459
00:41:37,260 --> 00:41:39,262
In rejecting you, perhaps?

460
00:41:39,660 --> 00:41:41,150
I've long given up
thinking of that.

461
00:41:42,180 --> 00:41:43,989
Or wishing it, either.

462
00:41:46,620 --> 00:41:47,826
But I will say this.

463
00:41:47,900 --> 00:41:50,506
Leading on a man you
don't care for is beneath you.

464
00:41:53,380 --> 00:41:56,702
I cannot allow a man to
criticize my private conduct.

465
00:41:56,820 --> 00:41:58,940
You will please leave the farm
at the end of the week.

466
00:42:07,180 --> 00:42:09,182
I'd prefer to go at once.

467
00:42:09,500 --> 00:42:12,026
Then go. I never want to
see your face again.

468
00:42:14,060 --> 00:42:16,188
Very well, Miss Everdene.

469
00:42:52,860 --> 00:42:55,670
Whoa, there we are.
There.

470
00:42:59,580 --> 00:43:01,070
What's wrong with them?

471
00:43:01,500 --> 00:43:03,184
They broke fence
and ate the young clover.

472
00:43:03,260 --> 00:43:04,466
Makes their stomachs swell.

473
00:43:06,580 --> 00:43:07,741
Well,
what do we do now?

474
00:43:07,820 --> 00:43:09,822
Nothing.
The whole flock is blasted.

475
00:43:10,060 --> 00:43:11,585
You mean they're
all going to die?

476
00:43:11,660 --> 00:43:12,661
Most probably.

477
00:43:12,820 --> 00:43:13,821
Another one gone here, ma'am.

478
00:43:13,900 --> 00:43:16,028
Only one way of saving them.

479
00:43:16,100 --> 00:43:18,865
You must pierce
their side with a tool.

480
00:43:19,260 --> 00:43:22,150
A hollow tube.
Pricker inside.

481
00:43:22,260 --> 00:43:23,989
Well, can you do it?

482
00:43:24,220 --> 00:43:25,426
This one's still alive.

483
00:43:25,580 --> 00:43:26,786
No.

484
00:43:26,900 --> 00:43:28,868
Can I?
Oh, good Lord, no.

485
00:43:29,420 --> 00:43:31,070
One inch to
the right or the left,

486
00:43:31,140 --> 00:43:33,142
and you kill the ewe for sure.

487
00:43:33,260 --> 00:43:37,151
Not even a shepherd
can do it, as a rule.

488
00:43:37,780 --> 00:43:39,384
Well, who, then?

489
00:43:55,220 --> 00:43:56,665
Gabriel!

490
00:43:58,260 --> 00:43:59,671
Gabriel!

491
00:43:59,780 --> 00:44:01,862
Gabriel Oak, wait!

492
00:44:03,420 --> 00:44:04,626
Miss Everdene needs you.

493
00:44:10,340 --> 00:44:13,981
Why are you alone?
Did you find him?

494
00:44:14,380 --> 00:44:15,711
Yes, miss.

495
00:44:16,660 --> 00:44:17,991
So what did he say?

496
00:44:19,900 --> 00:44:21,311
He said...

497
00:44:22,860 --> 00:44:24,191
Joseph?

498
00:44:25,420 --> 00:44:26,580
He said you're to go in person

499
00:44:26,620 --> 00:44:28,300
and request him civilly
in a proper manner.

500
00:44:29,900 --> 00:44:32,267
Where does he get his airs?
I'll do no such thing.

501
00:44:33,980 --> 00:44:35,470
He said you'd say that.

502
00:44:35,540 --> 00:44:38,862
He said to reply,
"Beggars can't be choosers."

503
00:44:59,540 --> 00:45:01,429
Mr. Oak.

504
00:45:04,060 --> 00:45:05,346
Gabriel.

505
00:45:07,260 --> 00:45:08,830
Gabriel.

506
00:45:10,980 --> 00:45:13,062
Please don't desert me, Gabriel.

507
00:45:15,020 --> 00:45:16,545
I need your help.

508
00:45:36,740 --> 00:45:38,629
Make room for me.

509
00:46:07,540 --> 00:46:08,587
I wanna see.

510
00:46:08,660 --> 00:46:09,866
No, don't you start,
Liddy, be quiet.

511
00:46:09,980 --> 00:46:11,869
Find the spot.

512
00:46:14,300 --> 00:46:15,790
Between the ribs.

513
00:46:18,500 --> 00:46:20,025
Oh, Lord!
No, no, no, no, no.

514
00:46:20,140 --> 00:46:21,824
Now...

515
00:46:22,300 --> 00:46:24,302
I can see
his heart beating.

516
00:46:28,780 --> 00:46:29,980
Come on.
- Come on, girl.

517
00:46:31,300 --> 00:46:32,426
Come on.

518
00:46:32,500 --> 00:46:34,100
She'll be all right.
She'll be all right.

519
00:46:34,140 --> 00:46:35,585
You all right?
You all right, Pixie?

520
00:46:35,700 --> 00:46:37,145
Yeah, come on.

521
00:46:37,220 --> 00:46:38,460
All right, Pixie! Pixie!

522
00:46:40,780 --> 00:46:42,384
Hey! Come here!

523
00:47:12,540 --> 00:47:14,986
<i>Lay me low</i>

524
00:47:15,820 --> 00:47:18,061
<i>Lay me low</i>

525
00:47:18,900 --> 00:47:22,985
<i>Where no-one can see me</i>

526
00:47:23,980 --> 00:47:27,143
<i>Where no-one can find me</i>

527
00:47:27,500 --> 00:47:32,586
<i>Where no-one can hurt me</i>

528
00:47:41,580 --> 00:47:42,581
Get out.

529
00:47:43,740 --> 00:47:45,583
Please, quiet.

530
00:47:47,420 --> 00:47:54,269
<i>Oh, early one morning
As I was a walking</i>

531
00:47:55,700 --> 00:48:01,707
<i>The fields and the meadows
They looked so green and gay</i>

532
00:48:02,260 --> 00:48:05,264
<i>The birds sang so sweetly</i>

533
00:48:05,460 --> 00:48:08,828
<i>So pleasant and so charming</i>

534
00:48:09,180 --> 00:48:11,547
<i>So early in the morning</i>

535
